title: For Sale/Trade:  U.S.1918 Trench Knife
postcontent:
sold pending receipt of funds U.S.1918 Trench Knife  this rare fighting knife is the French contracted version with the AU Lion on the blade. It is in excellent condition and is uncleaned and unaltered. The knife belonged to a man born in the 19th century and was a WWI vet.  It was believed to have been brought back from the war.  $575. OBO  text REDACTED

Original U.S. Model 1918 Trench Knife. Manufactured under contract by the French firm Au Lion for our doughboys during World War One. The French knives were the first to be issued as it took the US companies some time to tool up. Experts believe the Au Lion was the only Model 1918 Trench knife to see actual combat during the WW I. The Model 1918 remained U.S. standard issue up until WWII and did see some use WW II. 6-5/8" double edged blade with cast brass knuckle guard/handle and "skull crusher" pommel.

title: For Sale:  SIG P210-4 “Kuba Modell” in 9x19mm Para
postcontent:
This is an original Swiss-made SIG P210-4, serial number 6494, chambered in 9x19mm Para. It is part of the final delivery of the so-called “Kuba Pistolen” to Hoffmann & Reinhardt of Zürich. The pistol has an excellent bore suggesting a low round count with standard pressure ammunition in conjunction with minimal wear marks on the breech. It retains about 95% of the original matte blue finish, with light edge and high spot wear and minor thinning on the lower frame. 

H.P. Doebeli, the first chronicler of the P210, applied the denomination of the “Kuba Modell” to a batch of surplus P210-4, a part of the 1,500 pistols produced in advance by SIG expecting orders from the German government following their 1951 delivery to the Bundesgrenzschutz. When the German order failed to materialize, 1,417 of these pistols were sent to Denmark as the third delivery of their m/49 military contract. (See Vetter, p. 69.) Originally numbered as a continuation of the German BGS order between 5025 and 6441, the pistols redirected to Denmark were renumbered by prefixes with the numeral 3, yielding the range 35025-36441. The tail end of this production run, unclaimed by the Danes, and numbered between 6442 and 6500, remained at first in Switzerland. Vetter shows SN 6491, the last P210 delivered to the Basel police, and the final SN 6500, on p. 74. The gun in this auction is numbered between these two. It bears U.S. importer marks of “Benet Arms, S.F. Cal.94-4079”, applied around the magazine well

Danish army shot many kinds of 9mm ammo, including the Bofors M39B. This caused the slides to crack between the opening for the loaded chamber indicator and the ejection port. In early Sixties, SIG delivered unmarked replacement slides, but since they were already hardened, the numbers engraved by the armorers were not as deep as the original roll marks on the frame. Armbruster’s book shows on p. 137 one of the m/49 pistols, SN 35763, retrofitted with an upgraded slide for delivery to Denmark.

This fine and rare pistol represents the original SIG P210 design in its last and most definitive embodiment to date. It is fit to serve as the centerpiece of the most advanced SIG P210 collection. It rests in a locking factory leather presentation case. High resolution photos can be seen here

title: For Sale/Trade:  HK SL8
postcontent:
The Heckler & Koch SL8 is a sporting rifle manufactured by Heckler & Koch. It is the civilian version of the Heckler & Koch G36.  The rifle fires the .223 Remington or 5.56x45mm NATO cartridge and feeds from a 10, 20 or 30 round detachable magazine (depending on the variant of the rifle). Unlike earlier types of HK rifles, it is not a roller lock bolt but rather a lug type rotating bolt system as seen on the AR-18. The SL8 was originally developed for the German Bundeswehr, to provide a weapon for training reservists similar to the G36 and able to be provided to reserve organizations not able to provide military grade armaments.  Source: www.Wikipedia.com

This rifle has been kept in my safe since picking it up used.  It is exceptionally clean and appears to have the factory grease in the chamber.  It will be difficult to find a rifle in better condition.  Perfect starting point for a g36 conversion project or a collectible.

title: For Sale:  FN FNH FS2000 - Black with low round count
postcontent:
I have a mint condition FS2000 Tactical that I'm selling.  Under 200 rounds fired.  It's stock except the grip has had the plug removed for the installation of a surefire flashlight.  Includes stock iron sights, one mag, lock and paperwork.  

If you're not familiar with the FS2000, look at some of the online reviews.  It is a truly ambidextrous CQB rifle.  The spent casings move forward through an ejection tube and exit from the front of the rifle.  The casings fall to your feet in a neat pile instead of off and to the right somewhere.  They typically eat any ammo you can find, and this particular rifle is no exception.  I've never had a FTE, FTF, stovepipe, etc.  Clearing a jam is supposed to be easy as well.  Pull the mag, cycle the action 2 times, reinsert new mag and recharge.  I say "supposed to be easy" because I've never had to do it.  

And it's an attention getter.  In addition to this rifle, I have an FS2000 in OD, and a PS90.  These are the two I usually take to the range.  I always have people asking me about them and trying them out.  And virtually no-one doesn't like them.  Even die hard AR guys.  There's something elegant about these rifles, and no-one can refute the fact that they just run and run and run.  Just make sure the mag is inserted fully.

I'm willing to meet at Red's South if you want to try before you buy.  

For 1,925 I'll include the FN tri-rail which replaced the forward hand grip.  That's a $200 value.

I have many more photos if you want.

FTF preferred in the Austin area.  Requires Tx DL for FTF.

title: For Sale:  SPAS-12 Combat Self-Defense Shotgun
postcontent:
Cash or trade for Benelli M4 shotgun

I'm selling my Franchi SPAS-12 shotgun. It's in good condition and fully functional with less than average wear. It's been well maintained and not shot very much although, a LOT of fun to shoot.

Only about 1,850 SPAS-12's were imported into the US. This amounted to about 5% of production. The rest went mostly to European and Asian militaries and police. It's a  dual-mode shotgun that can be used in semi-automatic or pump-action operation. The SPAS 12 was designed to function primarily as a semi-automatic firearm, with the pump-action mode used to reliably fire low-pressure ammunition such as tear gas rounds or less-lethal bean bags. The firing mode is switched by pressing a button under the foregrip and sliding the foregrip slightly forwards or backwards until it clicks into position. The SPAS-12 has a magazine cut-off feature, which prevents loading a new round from the internal magazine when the gun is cycled. This allows the operator to load a specialized round into the chamber without firing the entire magazine first. The barrel of the SPAS 12 was externally threaded to accept many different attachments from chokes to gas-grenade launchers. The appearance and intended purpose of the SPAS-12 initially led to its "combat" designation. Franchi renamed the model the Sporting Purpose Automatic Shotgun in 1990, after the importation ban of 1989 (when it was called the Special Purpose Automatic Shotgun). This allowed continued sales to the U.S. until 1994. After the Clinton administration's Federal Assault Weapons Ban, exports to the U.S. stopped.

title: For Sale/Trade:  Grendel P-10 .380 auto
postcontent:
Will ship upon receipt of payment (willing to arrange neutral 3rd party), at buyers expense. Transfer by FFL, please do not ask for cash and carry, your $30 is not worth my rights.

This is a very interesting sub-micro-mini-compact pistol with respectable firepower it is the predecessor to Keltec (see the resemblance?). I am getting rid of this due to the fact that it is a little small for my hands. There are grip extensions for these out there though they are hard to come by. The original owner used this as a back-up piece because it’s tiny and offers 10 rounds of influence. It is double action only, has an internal (non-removable) magazine, a concealed hammer and low profile sights meaning it is perfect for non-snagging concealed carry. The Smith and Wesson Model 39 is a semi-automatic pistol developed for the US Army service pistol trials of 1954. Info for purchasers of our micro/mini uzi striker assembly: We have measured approximately 100 IMI mini and micro bolts plus a few other aftermarket mini and micro bolts. We have determined that they all vary dimensionally (even the IMI). We have also measured the mini and micro striker assemblies that we were able to acquire.
